  "id": "019d32b7-06b1-7262-bea2-2e6d68ffee06",
  "content": "# Research Spike: Agent Teams Environment and File Formats\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Method:** Created a real Agent Teams session (spike-env-capture) with 2 Haiku teammates, captured env vars and file contents via hooks.\n\n## Critical Finding: No Team-Specific Env Vars on Teammates\n\nTeammate processes get ONLY these CLAUDE_* env vars:\n- `CLAUDECODE=1`\n- `CLAUDE_CODE_ENTRYPOINT=cli`\n- `CLAUDE_CODE_EXPERIMENTAL_AGENT_TEAMS=1`\n\n**Missing (not exposed as env vars):**\n- No `CLAUDE_CODE_TEAM_NAME`\n- No `CLAUDE_CODE_AGENT_NAME`\n- No `CLAUDE_CODE_AGENT_ID`\n- No `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID`\n- No `CLAUDE_CODE_PARENT_SESSION_ID`\n\nThis means: teammate hooks CANNOT identify which team or role a process belongs to from env vars alone. The reverse-engineering article from dev.to was wrong about `CLAUDE_CODE_TEAM_NAME` being an env var. It is only in AsyncLocalStorage (JavaScript internal context), not in the shell environment.\n\n## config.json Full Schema (Verified)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"spike-env-capture\",\n  \"description\": \"...\",\n  \"createdAt\": 1774672217745,\n  \"leadAgentId\": \"team-lead@spike-env-capture\",\n  \"leadSessionId\": \"658150a6-...\",  // <-- LEAD SESSION ID IS IN CONFIG\n  \"members\": [\n    {\n      \"agentId\": \"team-lead@spike-env-capture\",   // format: {name}@{team-name}\n      \"name\": \"team-lead\",\n      \"agentType\": \"team-lead\",\n      \"model\": \"claude-opus-4-6[1m]\",\n      \"joinedAt\": 1774672217745,\n      \"tmuxPaneId\": \"\",\n      \"cwd\": \"/workspaces/corvia-workspace\",\n      \"subscriptions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"agentId\": \"docs-lister@spike-env-capture\",\n      \"name\": \"docs-lister\",\n      \"model\": \"haiku\",\n      \"prompt\": \"...\",              // <-- FULL SPAWN PROMPT STORED\n      \"color\": \"blue\",\n      \"planModeRequired\": false,\n      \"joinedAt\": 1774672260425,\n      \"tmuxPaneId\": \"in-process\",\n      \"cwd\": \"/workspaces/corvia-workspace\",\n      \"subscriptions\": [],\n      \"backendType\": \"in-process\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nKey discoveries:\n- `agentId` format is `{name}@{team-name}` (deterministic, not UUID)\n- `leadSessionId` is the lead's session UUID (bridges team config to session history)\n- Teammate `prompt` is stored in full (the spawn instruction)\n- `backendType` is \"in-process\" (vs tmux split pane)\n- No `sessionId` field for teammates (only the lead has `leadSessionId`)\n\n## Task File Schema (Verified)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"1\",\n  \"subject\": \"List docs/decisions/ files\",\n  \"description\": \"...\",\n  \"status\": \"pending\",   // pending | in_progress | completed | deleted\n  \"blocks\": [],\n  \"blockedBy\": []\n}\n```\n\nNo `owner`, `activeForm`, or timestamp fields when created via TaskCreate tool. The `owner` and `activeForm` appear when set via TaskUpdate.\n\n## Inbox Message Schema (Verified)\n\n```json\n[\n  {\n    \"from\": \"docs-lister\",\n    \"text\": \"{\\\"type\\\":\\\"idle_notification\\\",...}\",  // JSON-in-JSON for system messages\n    \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-28T04:31:06.736Z\",\n    \"color\": \"blue\",\n    \"read\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"from\": \"adapter-lister\",\n    \"text\": \"plain text message here\",              // plain text for user messages\n    \"summary\": \"Short preview text\",\n    \"timestamp\": \"...\",\n    \"color\": \"green\",\n    \"read\": true\n  }\n]\n```\n\n- Lock directory: `{agent-name}.json.lock/` (directory, not file)\n- System messages (idle_notification, shutdown_request) are JSON-in-JSON in the `text` field\n- User messages are plain text with optional `summary`\n\n## Hook Payload Schemas (Verified)\n\n**TaskCreated:**\n```json\n{\n  \"session_id\": \"658150a6-...\",        // lead's session ID\n  \"transcript_path\": \"/root/.claude/projects/.../658150a6-....jsonl\",\n  \"cwd\": \"/workspaces/corvia-workspace\",\n  \"hook_event_name\": \"TaskCreated\",\n  \"task_id\": \"1\",\n  \"task_subject\": \"...\",\n  \"task_description\": \"...\"\n}\n```\n\n**TeammateIdle:**\n```json\n{\n  \"session_id\": \"658150a6-...\",        // lead's session ID (NOT teammate's)\n  \"transcript_path\": \"...\",\n  \"cwd\": \"...\",\n  \"permission_mode\": \"default\",\n  \"hook_event_name\": \"TeammateIdle\",\n  \"teammate_name\": \"docs-lister\",      // <-- TEAMMATE NAME IS HERE\n  \"team_name\": \"spike-env-capture\"     // <-- TEAM NAME IS HERE\n}\n```\n\nCritical: TeammateIdle provides `teammate_name` and `team_name` in the hook payload. This is the bridge we need for correlation.\n\n## Impact on Design Decisions\n\n1. **Q2 (Agent ID correlation):** The `agentId` is `{name}@{team-name}`, deterministic. No UUID mapping needed. We can reconstruct it from name + team_name.\n\n2. **Q2 (Session ID correlation):** Only the lead's `sessionId` appears in config (`leadSessionId`). Teammate session IDs are NOT stored anywhere in team files. Must use the `session_id` from hook payloads (but TeammateIdle gives the LEAD's session_id, not the teammate's).\n\n3. **Q1 (Capture mechanism):** TeammateIdle hook gives us `teammate_name` + `team_name` on stdin. Combined with the ability to read team files from the hook, this is sufficient for incremental capture.\n\n4. **Q3 (Incremental capture):** TaskCreated hook does NOT include `teammate_name` or `team_name`. Only TeammateIdle does. This means task creation hooks fire in the lead's context, not the teammate's.\n\n## Remaining Gap\n\nTeammate session IDs are not stored in team config and not provided in hook payloads. To bridge a teammate to their session history entries, we need either:\n- A SessionStart hook that detects team membership (but no team env vars are set)\n- Temporal correlation (teammate joined at time T, session started at time T)\n- The `joinedAt` timestamp in config.json correlates with teammate process spawn time\n",
